history.content:
Chem 1A doesn't have a lab. You're thinking of Chem 1AL. You should Phase I Chem 1AL if you wish to take it. It is also only 1 unit.

You can Phase II Chem 1A, especially with your early appointment (although you may need to be a bit flexible with discussion time).

children.subject: Thanks for the advice. I chose chem because my other option is physics 7C, which has an 8am lecture next semester :/. I need to fulfill the EECS science requirement. Does anyone taken who's taken physics 7C have any comments or insight into the workload and difficulty of the class?

I took Chem 1A/1AL and thought it was a great class, especially since I hadn't taken AP Chem so I didn't know that much about Chemistry. Although one could definitely make the argument that between 2-4 hours/week (pretty easy prelab plus 3 hour lab period that sometimes ends early) isn't "worth it" for only getting one unit, if you can spare a few hours in your schedule I would strongly recommend it for the sake of intellectual curiosity. Plus they light stuff on fire pretty regularly

I would highly suggest not taking Chem 1A/L... EECS major in the course right now, it is quite a bit of work (especially the lab, it's a ridiculous amount of work for one unit) and it's not relevant in any way to what you're studying. Unless you're really into Chem I'd stay away

history.content: I'm a declared EECS major, and I'm trying to decide whether to Phase I CS161 or Chem1A. I'm currently enrolled in both of them, but once enrollment into CS186 is open, I think I'm going to need to drop one in order to enroll in 186. I've heard that I need to Phase I Chem1A to get a good lab time. Does anyone know if it would be safe to leave CS161 for Phase II? Or should I start preparing mentally for an 8am chem lab? My phase II is on 11/16. Any advice would be appreciated. Thanks!
